1
00:01:13,625 --> 00:01:15,625
Replacement team's here, sir.

2
00:01:15,750 --> 00:01:16,792
Right.

3
00:01:16,917 --> 00:01:18,875
Come on through.

4
00:01:20,208 --> 00:01:22,875
20 minutes and we were gonna
start looking for you.

5
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,375
Yeah. It's really something out there.

6
00:01:25,542 --> 00:01:27,500
- You look a mess, sir.
- Yeah?

7
00:01:27,583 --> 00:01:29,542
Your turn next, Ginsburg.

8
00:01:36,042 --> 00:01:38,000
OK. I'll see you in 24.

9
00:01:38,167 --> 00:01:39,750
See you tomorrow.

10
00:01:44,208 --> 00:01:46,250
What was that you were you saying?

11
00:01:46,375 --> 00:01:49,875
You used to hear her chant
all night long. Om mahneypod me om.

12
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:52,375
- Om mahneypod me om.
- Over the plants?

13
00:01:52,500 --> 00:01:55,625
She'd cup her hands over those seeds
and chant by the hour.

14
00:01:55,750 --> 00:01:58,708
She grew the most beautiful
wandoos you ever saw, man.

15
00:01:58,833 --> 00:02:00,792
Primo stuff. Resin city.

16
00:02:05,583 --> 00:02:07,542
Stand clear.

17
00:02:15,792 --> 00:02:19,125
The commander's been worried
about you. The roads must be a bear.

18
00:02:19,250 --> 00:02:21,333
- What roads?
- Visibility.

19
00:02:21,458 --> 00:02:25,958
Visibility? Bullshit. You guys haven't
been on time for the last six months.

20
00:02:26,083 --> 00:02:29,583
- I wrote you guys up in the logbook.
- Yeah. You're a prince, Bevan.

21
00:02:31,375 --> 00:02:33,333
Good night, gentlemen!

22
00:02:43,542 --> 00:02:45,708
So, that was like sinsemilia, right?

23
00:02:45,833 --> 00:02:49,417
Sinsemilla. This grass made
Thai stick taste like oregano.

24
00:02:49,542 --> 00:02:51,500
Lay you out flat, man.

25
00:02:55,417 --> 00:02:57,500
- Got a red light, sir.
- What on?

26
00:02:57,583 --> 00:02:59,500
Number eight. Warhead alarm.

27
00:02:59,625 --> 00:03:01,792
Give it a thump with your finger.

28
00:03:06,042 --> 00:03:08,250
Alarm reset.

29
00:03:21,917 --> 00:03:26,125
Skybird, this is Dropkick with
a Red dash Alpha message in two parts.

30
00:03:26,250 --> 00:03:28,208
Break. Break. Red dash Alpha.

31
00:03:28,375 --> 00:03:30,792
- Stand by to copy message.
- Standing by.

32
00:03:30,917 --> 00:03:34,083
Romeo Oscar November Charlie

33
00:03:34,250 --> 00:03:37,625
Tango Tango Lima Alpha.

34
00:03:37,750 --> 00:03:43,750
Authentication: 220040 Delta

35
00:03:43,917 --> 00:03:45,417
Lima.

36
00:03:45,500 --> 00:03:48,458
I have a valid message.
Stand by to authenticate.

37
00:03:48,542 --> 00:03:50,958
I agree with authentication also, sir.

38
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:09,583
- Enter launch code.
- Entering launch code.

39
00:04:15,375 --> 00:04:18,833
- Launch order confirmed.
- Holy shit!

40
00:04:23,542 --> 00:04:27,708
Target selection: complete.
Time on target sequence: complete.

41
00:04:27,875 --> 00:04:31,125
- Yield selection: complete.
- Begin countdown. Tminus 60.

42
00:04:31,250 --> 00:04:34,208
- All right. Let's do it. Insert launch key.
- Stand by.

43
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:37,750
- Launch key inserted.
- Roger.

44
00:04:37,875 --> 00:04:41,000
On my mark... rotate launch key to Set.

45
00:04:41,958 --> 00:04:44,542
Three... two... one...

46
00:04:45,333 --> 00:04:47,542
- Mark.
- Tminus 50.

47
00:04:57,292 --> 00:04:59,250
Roger. At Set.

48
00:05:05,083 --> 00:05:06,750
- Sir?
- Tminus 40.

49
00:05:06,917 --> 00:05:10,250
- Enable missiles.
- Number one enabled. Two enabled.

50
00:05:10,375 --> 00:05:13,500
- Three enabled.
- Get somebody on the goddamn phone.

51
00:05:16,292 --> 00:05:17,667
Seven... eight...

52
00:05:19,583 --> 00:05:21,500
Nine...

53
00:05:24,208 --> 00:05:25,750
Ten. All missiles enabled.

54
00:05:25,875 --> 00:05:29,917
- Get me Wing Command Post. Direct line.
- That's not the correct procedure.

55
00:05:30,042 --> 00:05:33,333
- Try SAC Headquarters on the HF.
- That's not the procedure.

56
00:05:33,458 --> 00:05:37,542
I want somebody on the goddamn phone
before I kill 20 million people.

57
00:05:41,208 --> 00:05:42,667
T minus 20.

58
00:05:42,792 --> 00:05:46,542
I got nothin' here! They might
have been knocked out already.

59
00:05:46,667 --> 00:05:48,250
Right.

60
00:05:48,375 --> 00:05:51,417
On my mark,
rotate launch keys to Launch.

61
00:05:51,542 --> 00:05:53,667
Roger. Ready to go to Launch.

62
00:05:53,833 --> 00:05:56,083
- Fourteen...
- Thirteen... twelve...

63
00:05:56,208 --> 00:05:57,458
Eleven...

64
00:06:00,375 --> 00:06:03,708
Seven... six...

65
00:06:03,833 --> 00:06:06,083
- Five...
- Sir, we have a launch order.

66
00:06:06,208 --> 00:06:09,208
- Three... two...
- Put your hand on the key, sir.

67
00:06:09,375 --> 00:06:11,125
One... Launch!

68
00:06:13,750 --> 00:06:18,000
- Sir, we are at launch! Turn your key!
- I'm sorry. I'm so sorry.

69
00:06:18,167 --> 00:06:20,583
Turn your key, sir!

70
00:08:05,542 --> 00:08:07,583
They're cleared. Go ahead and open it up.

71
00:08:11,167 --> 00:08:15,417
- Hello. I'm Pat Healy.
- I'm Lyle Watson. This is Arthur Cabot.

72
00:08:15,542 --> 00:08:19,917
I'm Pat Healy, Dr McKittrick's assistant.
I've got some passes for you here.

73
00:08:20,083 --> 00:08:22,792
We had scheduled a meeting
pending your arrival.

74
00:08:22,917 --> 00:08:25,542
If you have any questions,
feel free to ask me.

75
00:08:25,625 --> 00:08:28,625
I'd be happy to fill you in
if there's any way I can.

76
00:09:21,083 --> 00:09:23,042
They're here.

77
00:09:23,167 --> 00:09:24,667
Good.

78
00:09:24,792 --> 00:09:26,250
Let's go.

79
00:09:27,750 --> 00:09:31,250
Cabot and Watson came alone.
No senators. No congressmen.

80
00:09:31,417 --> 00:09:35,542
I wish they'd brought a few senators.
I'd like to tell 'em what's going on here.

81
00:09:35,667 --> 00:09:38,292
John, please! Don't start that right away.

82
00:09:38,417 --> 00:09:40,833
I had them on the phone
and they're calmed down.

83
00:09:42,625 --> 00:09:47,917
Well, are we positive that these men had
no way of knowing this was only a test?

84
00:09:48,042 --> 00:09:51,542
Lyle, for God's sakes! How many times
are we gonna go through this?

85
00:09:51,792 --> 00:09:54,958
- It doesn't make any difference.
- I've spoken to these men.

86
00:09:55,083 --> 00:09:57,333
They all believed it was the real deal.

87
00:09:57,458 --> 00:10:00,083
Look, we gotta be on a plane
in less than an hour.

88
00:10:00,208 --> 00:10:04,208
I have to explain to the president
why 22% of his missile commanders

89
00:10:04,333 --> 00:10:08,875
failed to launch their missiles. What
am I supposed to say? 22% isn't so bad?

90
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:13,542
The president knows that I am fully
responsible for the men in my command.

91
00:10:13,625 --> 00:10:17,458
I've ordered a re-evaluation of
our psychological screening procedure.

92
00:10:17,542 --> 00:10:19,750
Wait a minute. Excuse me, General.

93
00:10:19,875 --> 00:10:22,833
We can't ask these men
to go back to the president

94
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:27,125
with a lot of headshrinker horseshit!
You can't screen out human response!

95
00:10:27,250 --> 00:10:31,833
Those men know what it means to turn
the keys, and some are just not up to it!

96
00:10:31,958 --> 00:10:34,542
Now, it's as simple as that!

97
00:10:37,917 --> 00:10:40,708
I think we oughta take
the men out of the loop.

98
00:10:40,833 --> 00:10:44,292
- Mr McKittrick, you're out of line, sir.
- Why am I out of line?

99
00:10:44,417 --> 00:10:45,875
Excuse me!

100
00:10:47,125 --> 00:10:50,458
I'm sorry. I don't understand.
Take them out of the loop?

101
00:10:50,583 --> 00:10:53,250
Gentlemen! We've had men in these silos

102
00:10:53,375 --> 00:10:56,750
since before any of you
were watching Howdy Doody.

103
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:03,458
For myself, I sleep pretty well at night
knowing those boys are down there.

104
00:11:03,542 --> 00:11:07,542
General, we know they're fine men,
but in a nuclear war we can't afford

105
00:11:07,625 --> 00:11:10,333
to have missiles
lying dormant in those silos

106
00:11:10,458 --> 00:11:14,125
because those men refuse to turn
the keys when the computers tell 'em to!

107
00:11:14,250 --> 00:11:16,375
You mean when
the president orders them to.

108
00:11:16,542 --> 00:11:21,042
The president will probably follow
the computer war plan. That's a fact!

109
00:11:21,167 --> 00:11:23,792
I imagine the Joint Chiefs
will have some input.

110
00:11:23,917 --> 00:11:26,458
- You're damn tootin'.
- Well, hell...

111
00:11:26,583 --> 00:11:28,958
In a surprise attack, there's no time.

112
00:11:29,083 --> 00:11:31,542
23 minutes from warning to impact.

113
00:11:31,625 --> 00:11:34,667
- Six minutes if it's sub-launched.
- Six minutes.

114
00:11:34,792 --> 00:11:38,500
That's barely enough time
for the president to make a decision.

115
00:11:38,583 --> 00:11:41,417
Once he makes the decision,
the computer should take over.

116
00:11:41,542 --> 00:11:45,125
Now, sir, I know that you've got
a plane waiting for you,

117
00:11:45,250 --> 00:11:48,583
but if you could indulge me,
I'd like to show you something.

118
00:11:55,667 --> 00:11:59,000
These computers give instant access
to the state of the world.

119
00:11:59,125 --> 00:12:02,417
Troop movements, Soviet
missile tests, weather patterns.

120
00:12:02,583 --> 00:12:06,250
It all flows into this room,
and then into the WOPR computer.

121
00:12:06,375 --> 00:12:09,750
- WOPR? What is that?
- War Operation Plan Response.

122
00:12:09,875 --> 00:12:11,625
This is Mr Richter.

123
00:12:11,750 --> 00:12:15,500
Paul, would you like to tell
these gentlemen about the WOPR?

124
00:12:15,583 --> 00:12:19,875
Well, the WOPR spends all its time
thinking about World War Ill.

125
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:26,958
24 hours a day, 365 days a year,
it plays an endless series of war games

126
00:12:27,083 --> 00:12:30,542
using all available information
on the state of the world.

127
00:12:30,625 --> 00:12:34,375
The WOPR has already fought
World War Ill, as a game,

128
00:12:34,542 --> 00:12:36,500
time and time again.

129
00:12:36,583 --> 00:12:39,667
It estimates Soviet responses
to our responses

130
00:12:39,792 --> 00:12:42,000
to their responses, and so on.

131
00:12:42,125 --> 00:12:44,583
Estimates damage. Counts the dead.

132
00:12:44,708 --> 00:12:47,375
Then it looks for ways
to improve its score...

133
00:12:47,542 --> 00:12:49,833
The point is that the key decisions

134
00:12:49,958 --> 00:12:52,958
of every option have already
been made by the WOPR.

135
00:12:53,083 --> 00:12:56,583
So all this trillion-dollar hardware
is really at the mercy

136
00:12:56,708 --> 00:12:59,000
of those men with the little brass keys?

137
00:12:59,125 --> 00:13:02,667
That's exactly right. Whose only problem
is that they're human beings.

138
00:13:02,792 --> 00:13:07,458
But in 30 days we could put in electronic
relays. Get the men out of the loop.

139
00:13:07,583 --> 00:13:09,125
Gentlemen...

140
00:13:10,250 --> 00:13:14,625
I wouldn't trust this overgrown pile of
microchips further than I could throw it.

141
00:13:14,792 --> 00:13:20,208
I don't know if you wanna trust the safety
of our country to some... silicon diode...

142
00:13:20,333 --> 00:13:23,792
Nobody is talking about entrusting
the safety of the nation

143
00:13:23,917 --> 00:13:25,875
to a machine, for God's sake!

144
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:28,917
We'll keep control,
but here at the top where it belongs.

145
00:13:29,042 --> 00:13:30,417
All right, gentlemen.

146
00:13:30,542 --> 00:13:34,500
I think I'm going to recommend
McKittrick's idea to the president.

147
00:13:34,625 --> 00:13:37,000
And I'll get back to you on this.

148
00:13:38,750 --> 00:13:40,667
You won't regret this.

149
00:14:01,958 --> 00:14:04,083
OK. You had fries and a Coke, right?

150
00:14:21,875 --> 00:14:23,833
Damn!

151
00:14:26,250 --> 00:14:28,208
- Hi, David!
- Hi, Howie!

152
00:14:29,250 --> 00:14:31,208
- How's it going?
- Pretty good.

153
00:14:34,583 --> 00:14:37,333
- You wanna take this over? I gotta go.
- Sure!

154
00:14:37,458 --> 00:14:39,417
- Go ahead.
- Thanks!

155
00:14:42,917 --> 00:14:44,875
- Bye, David!
- Bye!

156
00:14:54,042 --> 00:14:57,792
All right. Question number two.

157
00:14:57,917 --> 00:15:05,458
Seeds that are germinated in water
before they are planted will... what?

158
00:15:05,583 --> 00:15:07,792
- Robert?
- Sprout roots?

159
00:15:07,958 --> 00:15:09,583
Ah! David!

160
00:15:09,667 --> 00:15:14,000
Nice of you to join us.
Oh, David. I have a little present for you.

161
00:15:24,333 --> 00:15:27,583
Question number four.
In the history of science,

162
00:15:27,667 --> 00:15:31,125
novel and innovative concepts
occasionally arise

163
00:15:31,250 --> 00:15:33,625
from sudden left-field inspiration.

164
00:15:33,750 --> 00:15:35,458
Miss Mack...

165
00:15:35,583 --> 00:15:38,792
Could you tell us your answer
to question number four?

166
00:15:38,917 --> 00:15:42,292
Why do nitrogen nodules
cling to the roots of plants?

167
00:15:44,750 --> 00:15:46,708
Love?

168
00:15:49,667 --> 00:15:54,042
Jennifer, what do you know about
nitrogen nodules that we don't?

169
00:15:54,167 --> 00:15:57,542
Some bit of salacious info
to which you alone are privy?

170
00:15:58,125 --> 00:16:00,083
- No.
- I see.

171
00:16:00,208 --> 00:16:03,375
No, you didn't know
the correct answer - symbiosis.

172
00:16:04,750 --> 00:16:07,708
Because you don't pay attention in class.

173
00:16:11,208 --> 00:16:13,167
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

174
00:16:13,333 --> 00:16:18,375
There seems to be a lot of confusion on
this next question - asexual reproduction.

175
00:16:19,583 --> 00:16:21,542
Could someone tell me, please

176
00:16:21,583 --> 00:16:26,750
who first suggested the idea
of reproduction without sex?

177
00:16:34,667 --> 00:16:36,292
- Miss Mack!
- Yes?

178
00:16:36,417 --> 00:16:38,917
What is so amusing?

179
00:16:41,875 --> 00:16:43,167
What?

180
00:16:43,292 --> 00:16:45,875
All right, Lightman.

181
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:51,000
Maybe you can tell us who first suggested
the idea of reproduction without sex.

182
00:16:51,125 --> 00:16:53,458
Your wife?

183
00:16:57,375 --> 00:16:59,542
Get out, Lightman! Get out!

184
00:17:07,542 --> 00:17:11,250
Mr Ligget wants me to discuss
my attitude problem with Mr Kessler.

185
00:17:11,375 --> 00:17:14,583
I think Mr Kessler's getting tired
of your attitude problem.

186
00:17:14,708 --> 00:17:16,292
Me, too.

187
00:17:45,875 --> 00:17:49,125
Lightman. What a... surprise.

188
00:17:49,250 --> 00:17:51,208
Won't you come in?

189
00:18:05,583 --> 00:18:07,583
Hi!

190
00:18:07,625 --> 00:18:08,625
Hi!

191
00:18:08,750 --> 00:18:11,667
Sorry if I got you in trouble.
I couldn't stop laughing.

192
00:18:11,792 --> 00:18:13,750
That's OK. You were perfect.

193
00:18:13,875 --> 00:18:15,833
- I was?
- Yeah.

194
00:18:15,958 --> 00:18:17,917
- You want a ride home?
- Yeah.

195
00:18:19,917 --> 00:18:21,875
Hop on.

196
00:18:28,792 --> 00:18:31,958
- So you got an F on that test today, too?
- Yep.

197
00:18:32,083 --> 00:18:34,750
Guess we're both gonna be
stuck in summer school.

198
00:18:34,875 --> 00:18:37,667
- Not me.
- Why not? You have to make up biology.

199
00:18:38,500 --> 00:18:40,625
- I don't think so.
- Why not?

200
00:18:42,208 --> 00:18:45,167
- Why not? Come on! Tell me. Why not?
- Make a left.

201
00:18:45,292 --> 00:18:48,292
Why don't you come up to my house
and I'll show you?

202
00:18:48,458 --> 00:18:50,417
What are you gonna show me?

203
00:18:50,542 --> 00:18:53,583
I'm gonna show you.
I'll show you how you do it.

204
00:18:54,917 --> 00:18:57,542
- Hi, Bo!
- Oh! Hi, Bo!

205
00:18:57,625 --> 00:18:59,583
Hey, Bo! How you doin'?

206
00:19:16,417 --> 00:19:18,375
My room's upstairs.

207
00:19:18,500 --> 00:19:21,458
- Your parents aren't home?
- No. They both work.

208
00:19:38,917 --> 00:19:40,833
A little mess.

209
00:19:40,958 --> 00:19:42,917
It's OK. You should see my room.

210
00:19:52,042 --> 00:19:54,833
- You're really into computers, huh?
- Yeah.

211
00:19:59,167 --> 00:20:03,250
- What are you doing?
- I'm dialing into the school's computer.

212
00:20:14,958 --> 00:20:19,542
They change the password every couple
of weeks, but I know where they write it.

213
00:20:32,583 --> 00:20:34,583
- Are those your grades?!
- Yeah.

214
00:20:35,458 --> 00:20:37,917
I don't think that I deserved an F, do you?

215
00:20:41,625 --> 00:20:44,167
- You can't do that!
- Already done.

216
00:20:46,667 --> 00:20:49,625
- Do you have a middle initial?
- K. Katherine.

217
00:20:55,042 --> 00:20:57,375
Those are my grades.

218
00:20:57,500 --> 00:21:01,083
- How can anybody get a D in home EC?
- That's none of your business.

219
00:21:01,208 --> 00:21:03,500
- Can you erase this?
- No. It's too late.

220
00:21:03,625 --> 00:21:05,417
What are you doing?

221
00:21:05,542 --> 00:21:09,292
- I'm changing your biology grade.
- No. You'll get me in trouble.

222
00:21:09,417 --> 00:21:13,208
Nobody can find out. You got a C!
Now you won't go to summer school.

223
00:21:13,333 --> 00:21:15,375
- Change it back.
- Why? They can't...

224
00:21:15,500 --> 00:21:18,542
- I said change it back.
- OK. OK.

225
00:21:26,417 --> 00:21:28,250
I guess I'd better get going.

226
00:21:29,708 --> 00:21:31,667
Thanks for the ride.

227
00:21:32,417 --> 00:21:34,542
Yeah. OK. Bye.

228
00:21:34,667 --> 00:21:36,625
Bye.

229
00:22:33,667 --> 00:22:37,708
Get down. Get down. You've already
had your dinner. Now just sit.

230
00:22:37,833 --> 00:22:39,833
Sit! Stay!

231
00:22:39,958 --> 00:22:42,625
- Don't forget to take out the garbage.
- David.

232
00:22:42,750 --> 00:22:45,542
- Put that lid on real tight.
- I know, Ma.

233
00:22:47,167 --> 00:22:49,750
Yes, they will carry back on the second.

234
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:54,375
Sure. I think we can really work out
some creative financing.

235
00:22:56,083 --> 00:22:58,042
Oh, but you've gotta see it!

236
00:22:58,208 --> 00:23:00,750
There's a Jacuzzi
in the master bedroom...

237
00:23:11,917 --> 00:23:14,000
Oh, sure. We can work that out.

238
00:23:14,958 --> 00:23:19,000
That is true. You'll have a balloon
